cs.DL, cs.IR, cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.CR

This paper discusses the limitations of the Journal Impact Factor (IF) and proposes alternative measures for evaluating the impact of scientific publications. The topics covered in the paper, such as citation distributions, normalization, and non-parametric statistics, are relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. Specifically, cs.DL (Digital Libraries) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are likely categories as they deal with the organization and retrieval of scientific publications. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.CY (Computers and Society) are also possible categories as they involve the analysis of social and cultural factors that influence scientific communication. Finally, cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) may be a less likely category, but it could be relevant if the paper discusses the security of citation data or the protection of intellectual property.
